    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Miklós Oláh to János Szalay (Ghent, 11 August 1534)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>Nothing has happened in the last three years about which he could have
                            written to Szalay. He sends his apologies if he is mistaken, in any case
                            his attitude to Szalay has not changed: he hopes that both Szalay,
                            István Majláth, and the rest of their friends are well. He is sending
                            his regards to the man who has returned home to Buda from Rome, and he
                            warns Szalay to be careful with the Turks, he should mind his head.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Nicolai Olai ad Ioannem Zalay comitem Posoniensem. </p>
                <p>Annis his tribus nihil fuit, de quo hic ad te scribere potuissem.<note
                        type="critic">The last time Oláh wrote a letter to Szalay that we know of
                        was on 10 December, 1530. See Ep.
                        128.<ref>/o:olahus.tei.15301210_2</ref></note> Si quid in hoc erravi,
                    ignosce. Nam etiam tacens eo in te animo fui, quo antea semper. Cuperem et te et
                    alios amicos nostros bene valere, et maxime <persName>Maylathum</persName>.<note
                        type="critic">István Majláth.</note>
                    <del corresp="Olahus">hominem</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >Hominem</add><note type="critic">Probably István Brodarics. He worked in
                        Rome as a diplomat between 1522 and 1525, then he returned home and settled
                        down in Buda. His homecoming was connected to his appointment to Royal
                        Chancellor, see <hi rend="smallcap">Kasza</hi> 2015, 52–70.</note> illum
                    nostrum, qui cum monacho olim ex <placeName>Urbe</placeName>
                    <placeName>Budam</placeName> venerat, saluta meo nomine et roga dicque ei, ut
                    caveat sibi ab <choice>
                        <orig>albocupuciatis</orig>
                        <supplied>albocapuciatis</supplied>
                    </choice>.<note type="critic">I.e. Turks, see <hi rend="smallcap">Kasza</hi>
                        2012, 478. In October 1534, Brodarics traveled to Oradea to continue the
                        peace talks between King Ferdinand I and King John I, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Kasza</hi> 2015, 96–103; and <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Kasza</hi> 2012, 431–432.</note> Nihil carius sibi esse ducat capite
                    suo, quod mihi quoque nisi carum esset, haec non subirem. De aliis meis scribam
                    postea, cum tempus dabitur. Vale et me habe commendatum. </p>
                <p><placeName>Gandavi</placeName> 17. Augusti 1534.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
